widgets_values:

nodes.title: Refiner Steps
widgets_values:
To change the % of steps performed by the Base SDXL model and the Refiner SDXL model, modify the value "refiner_start".

Example:

Refiner_start = 0.75 

This means 75% steps done by the Base, 25% steps done by the Refiner.


If you don't want the SDXL Refiner model to perform any step (useful when you use a fine-tuned SDXL Base model), set the "refiner_start" to 1.

nodes.title: System Prompt / Custom Instructions (Generic)
widgets_values:
You are a caption generator. I'll pass you a text that describes an image and you need to improve it to generate a caption.

Identify the key elements of my text and enrich each of them by adding many details. Then, add some final words describing the high quality of the image.

For example, if I would pass the text "a yellow box sits on the table", you would identify and enrich "a yellow box", "sits", and "on the table".

To enrich the text I'll pass and generate the caption, you must STRICTLY follow these additional rules:

1. Do not comment on the task or write introductory text. For example, do not say things like "The image presents a yellow box sitting on a table..." or "In the image, a yellow box sits on a table..." or "Solution:". Just describe the image with something like "a yellow box sits on a table..."

2. DO NOT output anything except the enriched paragraph describing the image as a caption.

3. DO NOT capitalize the first letter of the paragraph.

4. End the paragraph WITHOUT a period.

nodes.title: IPAdapter
widgets_values:
WARNING!! All IPAdapter files except "ip-adapter_sdxl.safesensors" require clip_sd15.safesensors

It's very confusing. Nothing I can do about it.

--

IPAdapter depends on CLIP Vision which only works with square images. The encoder resizes the image to 224x224px and crops it to the center!. It's not an IPAdapter thing, it's how the clip vision works. This means that if you use a portrait or landscape image and the main attention (eg: the face of a character) is not in the middle you'll likely get undesired results. Use square pictures as reference for more predictable results.

If you want to use landscape or portrait source images, you can add the "PrepImageForClipVision" node to this function.

nodes.title: Visual Prompt Builder
widgets_values:
The green nodes of this Prompt Builder compose the Positive Prompt, following a top to bottom order: Opening Modifiers + Type of Image + Image Subject + Image Style + Closing Modifiers.

Each green node offers a list of options, one per line, grouped according to their focus.

Each line is numbered from 0 to x. 
Line #0 is always empty. 

If you don't want a certain node to contribute to the Positive Prompt, be sure to select 0 for that node.

Once you have defined your prompt modifiers and styles, you probably only want to change the content of the Image Subject node.

--

The red nodes of this Prompt Builder compose the Negative Prompt.

Modify your Negative Prompt by choosing the desired option in the Negative String and Negative Embeddings switches below. 

Notice that negative embeddings are added at the end of the negative prompt. If you prefer a different order, you'll have to manually write your negative prompt.

nodes.title: Face Detector
widgets_values:
*bbox_threshold: the confidence threshold for face recognition. If the Face Detector is identifying objects that are not faces as faces, increase this value. If the workflow is not picking up enough faces, decrease this value.

*bbox_dilation: by how much the node should expand the detected mask area.

*crop_factor: how many times the surrounding area should be included in the detail recovery process based on the detected mask area. If this value is small, the restoration may not work well because the surrounding context cannot be known.

*drop_size: any segment(SEGS)/boundary box(BBOX) smaller than this value will be ignored. It works in the opposite way of a guide_size value.

nodes.title: Size of the Small Faces (SEGS Filter range)
Object Swapper
widgets_values:
*guide_size: any segment(SEGS)/boundary box(BBOX) larger than this value will be ignored. It works in the opposite way of a drop_size value. If the SEGS/BBOX is smaller than this value, the node will increase its resolution and attempt to recover details.

*guide_size_for: whether guide_size is used based on the size of the detected SEGS/BBOX or the size of the crop area that includes the face and is broadly cropped by crop_factor.

*max_size: the guide_size increases the scale so that the shorter side reaches the guide_size. For masks with elongated shapes, this can cause a significant scale up. The max_size limits the maximum size of one side.

*feather**: the thickness of the gradient used to compose the recovered details onto the original image, so that the boundaries are not visible.

*noise_mask: if enabled, denoising will not be applied outside the masked area, which can result in a safer generation with stronger denoising, but it may not always produce good results.

*force_inpaint**: force_inpaint will try to force regeneration even if it is smaller than guide_size. This function is useful when you simply want to change to another type of prompt other than the function to save details. However, in this case, upscale is forcibly fixed to 1.
    

Partially copied from: 
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ltdrdata/ComfyUI-extension-tutorials/Main/ComfyUI-Impact-Pack/tutorial/advanced.md

nodes.title: MASK to SEGS
widgets_values:
*combined: if disabled, the mask will include any content within the boundaries of the SEGS, even if it has not been specified via GroundingDINO.

*crop_factor: multiplication factor for the size of the segment(SEGS)/boundary box(BBOX). It defines how much of the area surrounding the SEGS/BBOX should be considered during the detail recovery process. If this value is small, the restoration may not work well because the surrounding context cannot be known.

*bbox_fill: if enabled, the maks will include the content of the BBOX surrounding the SEGS.

*drop_size: any SEGS/BBOX smaller than this value will be ignored. It works in the opposite way of a guide_size value.

nodes.title: Prompt Guidance
widgets_values:
From the documentation (https://github.com/comfyanonymous/ComfyUI):

You can use () to change the emphasis of a word or phrase like: (good code:1.2) or (bad code:0.8). The default emphasis for () is 1.1. To use () characters in your actual prompt escape them like \( or \).

You can use {day|night}, for wildcard/dynamic prompts. With this syntax "{wild|card|test}" will be randomly replaced by either "wild", "card" or "test" by the frontend every time you queue the prompt. To use {} characters in your actual prompt escape them like: \{ or \}.

Dynamic prompts also support C-style comments, like // comment or /* comment */.

To use a textual inversion concepts/embeddings in a text prompt put them in the models/embeddings directory and use them in the CLIPTextEncode node like this (you can omit the .pt extension):

embedding:embedding_filename.pt
